bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical note
bioghist.p: Nelson A. Rockefeller served as governor of New York from January 1, 1959, to December 18, 1973. He was the first person elected to four consecutive four-year terms as a state governor.

arrangement.head: Arrangement note
arrangement.p: There are nine subseries in this series.

Subseries 1 - Politics, 1959-1960 Subseries 2 - Politics, 1961-1962 Subseries 3 - Politics, 1963-1964 Subseries 4 - Politics, 1965, 1967 Subseries 5 - Politics, 1968-1969 Subseries 6 - Politics, 1970-1971 Subseries 7 - Politics, 1972-1973 Subseries 8 - Thank-You Letters, 1968-1972 Subseries 9 - Assorted Campaign and Political Materials, 1962-1970

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series is composed of constituent correspondence during Nelson A. Rockefeller's four terms as governor of New York, from 1959 to 1973, and particularly the elections in 1958, 1962, 1966, and 1970. The series also reflects Rockefeller's presidential campaign efforts in 1964 and 1968. The bulk of the material is correspondence between the Governor's office and state constituents, as well as citizens from across the country and around the world.

arrangement.head: Arrangement note
arrangement.p: This subseries is arranged chronologically, and then alphabetically by correspondent.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This subseries, similar to the next six, contains the typical documents found in the bulk of this series, namely constituent correspondence to and from Governor Rockefeller. This subseries contains letters sent to Governor Rockefeller that were answered, those that were unanswered (labeled "no answer"), and some of the replies from 1959 to 1960. The files for L-Max are missing for both 1959 and 1960. Unique to this subseries, which documents the beginning of his 15-year tenure as governor, is the "Dinners and Luncheons" section that details functions in 1959. These folders include information on event arrangements and copies of the governor's remarks, sometimes with handwritten changes. Lastly, the distinction between "New York State Correspondence" and "New York State and Political Correspondence" is that the latter includes correspondence from outside New York State.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This final subseries contains materials that fall outside of the scope of the previous eight. There are many items that pertain to significant Republican campaigns. Included in this subseries are items such as campaign kits, lists of campaign workers, budgets, lists of Republican convention delegates by state, and congratulatory telegrams sent by Governor Rockefeller. The final portion of this subseries comprises several folders of lobbying memos for both the state Assembly and the state Senate. These memos and the accompanying correspondence by various lobbying groups and individuals either support or oppose passage of bills introduced in the 1970 state legislative sessions.
